

= Actuary Roles at Reinsurance Companies

== Overview

Actuaries at reinsurance companies are the mathematical and analytical backbone of the organization, responsible for pricing complex risk transfers, modeling catastrophic events, managing capital requirements, and ensuring the firm's financial stability. Unlike actuaries at primary insurers who assess individual policyholder risks, reinsurance actuaries work with aggregated portfolios, evaluate accumulation risk across geographies and perils, and manage tail risk from low-frequency, high-severity events.

In Australia, major global reinsurers operate through local offices including Swiss Re Australia, Munich Re Australia, Hannover Re, and SCOR. These firms provide reinsurance coverage across life, health, property, and casualty lines, supporting Australian primary insurers with risk transfer, capital relief, and technical expertise.

Reinsurance actuarial work requires sophisticated modeling capabilities, deep understanding of insurance markets, and the ability to assess risks that may not have extensive historical data (such as cyber risk, climate change impacts, or pandemic risk). Actuaries must balance technical precision with commercial judgment, working closely with underwriters, claims teams, and clients (cedants - the primary insurers ceding risk).

This document outlines actuary roles at reinsurance companies, from entry-level graduate positions through to Chief Actuary, covering both Life & Health and Property & Casualty (P&C) reinsurance disciplines.

