== 1. Graduate Actuary / Actuarial Analyst

=== Hierarchy Level
Entry-level to 2 years of experience, typically pursuing actuarial qualification (Part I or Part II exams with the Actuaries Institute)

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Data Analysis & Validation*: Cleaning and analyzing cedant data (claims experience, exposure information, policy terms)
- *Experience Analysis*: Conducting mortality, morbidity, or claims frequency/severity studies on reinsured portfolios
- *Pricing Support*: Assisting senior actuaries with treaty pricing calculations, loading estimates, risk margin quantification
- *Model Development*: Building and maintaining actuarial models (mortality tables, claims triangles, catastrophe scenarios)
- *Portfolio Monitoring*: Tracking actual vs. expected experience on reinsurance treaties
- *Regulatory Reporting*: Supporting capital adequacy calculations (APRA Prudential Standards, RBC frameworks)
- *Documentation*: Preparing pricing memos, assumption papers, and model documentation
- *Research*: Investigating emerging risks, industry trends, and new actuarial methodologies

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Strong mathematical and statistical foundation (probability theory, statistical inference, stochastic processes)
- Proficiency in actuarial software (R, Python, SAS, Prophet for life insurance)
- Understanding of insurance and reinsurance fundamentals
- Excel modeling skills (VBA beneficial)
- Knowledge of actuarial standards (APRA Prudential Standards, Professional Standards issued by Actuaries Institute)
- Familiarity with reinsurance structures (quota share, surplus, excess of loss, stop loss, catastrophe XL)

*Interpersonal:*
- Attention to detail in data analysis and calculations
- Clear written communication for technical documentation
- Ability to explain complex concepts to non-actuaries
- Collaborative approach working with underwriters, claims, and finance teams
- Time management balancing client work with exam study

*Regulatory:*
- Understanding of APRA Prudential Standards for general insurance (GPS) and life insurance (LPS)
- Awareness of actuarial professional standards and code of conduct
- Knowledge of International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS 17 for insurance contracts)
- Understanding of Solvency II framework (for European parent companies)

