== 3. Reserving Actuary

=== Hierarchy Level
4-8 years of experience, Part III qualified or near-qualified

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Loss Reserving*: Establishing IBNR (Incurred But Not Reported) and case reserve adequacy for reinsurance portfolios
- *Reserve Analysis*: Conducting detailed actuarial reviews using chain ladder, Bornhuetter-Ferguson, frequency-severity methods
- *Financial Reporting*: Supporting quarterly and annual financial close, providing reserve estimates for financial statements
- *IFRS 17 Implementation*: Calculating risk adjustments, contractual service margins, and present value of future cash flows
- *Capital Modeling*: Determining ultimate loss distributions for capital adequacy assessments (APRA, internal models)
- *Run-off Management*: Monitoring development of claims on expired treaties, identifying adverse development trends
- *Assumption Setting*: Establishing and updating reserving assumptions (loss development patterns, claims inflation, reopening rates)
- *Audit Support*: Responding to internal audit, external audit, and APRA inquiries regarding reserve methodology

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Expert knowledge of loss reserving techniques (chain ladder, GLM methods, bootstrap simulation)
- Strong understanding of claims processes and development patterns
- Proficiency in statistical analysis and stochastic modeling
- Knowledge of IFRS 17 accounting standards and implementation
- Experience with reserving software (ResQ, Arius, R packages for reserving)
- Understanding of reinsurance contract structures and their impact on loss development
- Familiarity with capital modeling frameworks

*Interpersonal:*
- Strong communication with CFO, finance team, and auditors
- Ability to defend actuarial assumptions and methodology to stakeholders
- Collaborative approach with claims, underwriting, and risk teams
- Professional skepticism balanced with commercial pragmatism
- Comfort with ambiguity and judgment in uncertain situations

*Regulatory:*
- Expert knowledge of APRA reporting requirements (QRS, ARS forms)
- Understanding of auditing standards and actuarial control cycle
- Knowledge of actuarial professional standards on reserving (PS 300)
- Awareness of Solvency II and international reserving practices

=== Typical Work Modes

*Reserve Analysis (50-60%):*
- Conducting quarterly reserve analyses across all lines of business
- Updating loss development triangles and running actuarial projections
- Investigating movements in reserves and development trends
- Performing sensitivity analysis and stress testing
- Validating reserve adequacy against emerging experience

*Financial Reporting (20-25%):*
- Preparing reserve estimates for quarterly and annual financial statements
- Supporting IFRS 17 calculations and disclosures
- Responding to CFO and audit committee inquiries
- Documenting reserve methodology and assumptions
- Coordinating with external auditors

*Collaboration & Communication (15-20%):*
- Meeting with claims teams to understand large loss developments
